---
import MarketingLayout from '../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro';
import ForgeRunDiagram from '../components/ForgeRunDiagram.astro';

// Canonical Forge documentation links — update these when the docs move.
// These are the single source of truth for outbound references on this page.
const DOCS = {
  root:       '/docs/',
  runs:       '/docs/concepts/runs/',
  tasks:      '/docs/concepts/tasks/',
  gates:      '/docs/concepts/gates/',
  reds:       '/docs/concepts/reds/',
  agents:     '/docs/concepts/agents/',
  blackboard: '/docs/concepts/blackboard/',
  workflows:  '/docs/reference/workflows/',
  cli:        '/docs/reference/cli/',
} as const;
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="How Forge runs work"
  description="A conceptual map of Forge internals for engineers: runs, tasks, gates, reds, agents, and the SQLite blackboard."
>
  <article class="page-article">

    <header class="page-hero">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="hero-eyebrow">Engineer reference</p>
        <h1 class="hero-headline">How Forge runs work</h1>
        <p class="hero-subhead">
          A conceptual map of the Forge execution model — the six moving parts you need to understand
          before everything else clicks into place.
        </p>
        <p class="hero-meta">
          This page explains the concepts. For CLI flags, YAML schema, and workflow definitions,
          see the <a href={DOCS.root} class="inline-link">full documentation</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <nav class="toc-nav" aria-label="On this page">
      <div class="toc-inner">
        <p class="toc-label">On this page</p>
        <ol class="toc-list" role="list">
          <li><a href="#runs" class="toc-link">Runs</a></li>
          <li><a href="#tasks" class="toc-link">Tasks</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gates" class="toc-link">Gates</a></li>
          <li><a href="#reds" class="toc-link">Reds</a></li>
          <li><a href="#agents" class="toc-link">Agents</a></li>
          <li><a href="#blackboard" class="toc-link">The blackboard</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <div class="content-body">
      <div class="content-inner">

        <section class="concept-section" id="runs" aria-labelledby="runs-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">01</div>
          <h2 id="runs-heading" class="concept-heading">Runs</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>run</strong> is the top-level unit of work in Forge. You create one by describing
            what you want built — a feature request, a bug fix, a refactor — and Forge orchestrates
            everything else from there.
          </p>
          <p>
            A run has a lifecycle: it starts, moves through phases (plan, build, verify, review),
            pauses at decision points, and eventually reaches a terminal state (complete, failed, or
            cancelled). The lifecycle is deterministic: the same brief, the same workflow, the same
            model policy will produce the same phase sequence every time.
          </p>
          <p>
            Runs are identified by a stable ID that threads through every piece of state the run
            produces — tasks, agent outputs, gate decisions, test results. That ID is what you pass
            when you want to watch, advance, or inspect a run in progress.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.runs} class="concept-ref-link">Runs reference &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="concept-section" id="tasks" aria-labelledby="tasks-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">02</div>
          <h2 id="tasks-heading" class="concept-heading">Tasks</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>task</strong> is the unit of agent work within a run. Each phase of a run is
            composed of one or more tasks. A planning phase produces one task; a build phase in a
            fan-out configuration might run several tasks in parallel, each handled by a different
            agent container.
          </p>
          <p>
            Tasks are scoped. Each task agent receives exactly the context it needs — no more — so
            it cannot accidentally stomp on work happening in a sibling task. The task's inputs,
            outputs, and status are all recorded and addressable by the task's stable ID.
          </p>
          <p>
            Task results accumulate in the blackboard (more on that below), where later tasks can
            read what earlier tasks produced. The dependency order between tasks is defined by the
            workflow, not negotiated dynamically.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.tasks} class="concept-ref-link">Tasks reference &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="concept-section" id="gates" aria-labelledby="gates-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">03</div>
          <h2 id="gates-heading" class="concept-heading">Gates</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>gate</strong> is a decision point between run phases. A run does not advance
            from planning to building, or from building to testing, without passing through a gate.
          </p>
          <p>
            Gates come in two modes. An <em>auto gate</em> is evaluated programmatically — Forge
            reads the previous phase's output, applies the configured criteria, and advances or
            blocks automatically. A <em>human gate</em> pauses the run and waits for an explicit
            approval. You inspect the artifact, decide, and call <code>forge gate &lt;taskId&gt; --advance</code> or <code>--reject</code>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The gate is the leverage point. By placing a human gate at the plan phase, you get to
            read and approve the implementation plan before any code is written. That's the moment
            when the cost of changing direction is lowest.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.gates} class="concept-ref-link">Gates reference &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="concept-section" id="reds" aria-labelledby="reds-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">04</div>
          <h2 id="reds-heading" class="concept-heading">Reds</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>red</strong> is an adversarial review agent. Where implementer agents build
            things, red agents are chartered to find problems — bugs, security issues, deviations
            from the plan, missing edge cases.
          </p>
          <p>
            Reds are specialists. There are wide reds (general correctness), narrow reds
            (file-level scrutiny), security reds (threat modeling and vulnerability analysis),
            frontend reds (accessibility and rendering), and backend reds (data integrity and
            API contracts). A run's workflow defines which reds run and in what order.
          </p>
          <p>
            The red gate is a verdict gate. A red returns a verdict — <em>pass</em>, <em>warn</em>,
            or <em>block</em> — with findings. A block stops the run and surfaces the findings for
            human review. A warn is recorded but does not stop progress. The orchestrator decides
            whether to override a block; the audit trail records the decision.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.reds} class="concept-ref-link">Reds reference &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="concept-section" id="agents" aria-labelledby="agents-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">05</div>
          <h2 id="agents-heading" class="concept-heading">Agents</h2>
          <p>
            An <strong>agent</strong> in Forge is a Docker container running a Claude Code session
            seeded with a role-specific prompt. The container gets a read-write mount of your
            project, a task brief, and the outputs of prior tasks it depends on. It runs to
            completion, writes a structured result to <code>result.json</code>, and exits.
          </p>
          <p>
            The agent model is stateless between tasks. Each container starts clean, does its work,
            and produces a structured artifact. Forge provides the state continuity; the agents
            provide the work. This design means you can run ten agents in parallel without them
            interfering with each other.
          </p>
          <p>
            Agents are scoped by discipline. A frontend specialist agent gets a seed prompt tuned
            for UI and accessibility work; a security advisor gets a threat-modeling prompt; a
            test engineer gets a verification-focused prompt. The orchestrator routes work to the
            right discipline — an engineer agent does not decide to also run the tests.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.agents} class="concept-ref-link">Agents reference &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="concept-section" id="blackboard" aria-labelledby="blackboard-heading">
          <div class="concept-label" aria-hidden="true">06</div>
          <h2 id="blackboard-heading" class="concept-heading">The SQLite blackboard</h2>
          <p>
            Forge's state lives in a local SQLite database — the <strong>blackboard</strong>. Every
            run, every task, every gate decision, every agent result is a row in that database.
            Nothing lives in memory between runs; everything is durable and inspectable.
          </p>
          <p>
            The blackboard is why Forge can resume a run after a crash, why you can inspect a run
            that finished two days ago, and why the orchestrator can pick up watching a run across
            terminal sessions. The state is always in the database; the process is just a reader
            and writer.
          </p>
          <p>
            The SQLite choice is deliberate. The database is a single file on disk — no server to
            run, no network dependency, trivially backed up, trivially inspected with standard tools.
            You can <code>sqlite3 ~/.forge/forge.db</code> and read the run table directly. The
            schema is versioned and the migration path is tested; upgrading Forge does not corrupt
            existing run history.
          </p>
          <div class="concept-ref">
            <a href={DOCS.blackboard} class="concept-ref-link">Blackboard schema &rarr;</a>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="diagram-section" aria-labelledby="diagram-heading">
          <h2 id="diagram-heading" class="diagram-heading">A real Forge run</h2>
          <p class="diagram-lead">
            The diagram below is animated from a real run trace — events exported from the
            SQLite blackboard. Each stage's width reflects its share of the pipeline's work,
            and gates and reds appear where they actually occurred in the run.
          </p>
          <ForgeRunDiagram />
        </section>

        <section class="flow-section" aria-labelledby="flow-heading">
          <h2 id="flow-heading" class="flow-heading">How they fit together</h2>
          <p class="flow-lead">
            A request flows through Forge like this:
          </p>

          <ol class="flow-list">
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">1</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>You create a run</strong> with a brief describing the work.
                Forge writes the run record to the blackboard.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">2</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>The plan phase runs.</strong> A tech-lead agent reads the brief,
                produces a step-by-step implementation plan, and writes it as a task result.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">3</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>A gate pauses the run.</strong> If you configured a human gate here,
                you review the plan. Approve it and Forge moves to build. Reject it and Forge
                re-plans with your feedback.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">4</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>Build tasks run.</strong> Specialist agents implement each step of the
                plan, writing code and self-validating their output. Parallel steps run in
                separate containers simultaneously.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">5</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>Reds review the diff.</strong> Adversarial agents read the completed
                work looking for problems. Findings are recorded. Blocks pause the run for
                human review.
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flow-item">
              <div class="flow-step-badge" aria-hidden="true">6</div>
              <div class="flow-step-content">
                <strong>The run completes.</strong> All results, decisions, and agent outputs
                are in the blackboard, linked by run ID, ready to inspect.
              </div>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </section>

        <section class="bottom-nav-section" aria-labelledby="next-heading">
          <h2 id="next-heading" class="bottom-nav-heading">Go further</h2>
          <div class="bottom-nav-links">
            <a href={DOCS.cli} class="bottom-nav-card">
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-title">CLI reference</span>
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-desc">Every forge command, flag by flag.</span>
            </a>
            <a href={DOCS.workflows} class="bottom-nav-card">
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-title">Workflow definitions</span>
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-desc">The YAML schema for custom run workflows.</span>
            </a>
            <a href="/what-forge-does" class="bottom-nav-card">
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-title">What Forge does</span>
              <span class="bottom-nav-card-desc">The non-technical overview for your team.</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </section>

      </div>
    </div>

  </article>
</MarketingLayout>

<style>
  .page-article {
    color: var(--forge-color-text);
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-body);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-base);
    line-height: var(--forge-line-height-relaxed);
  }

  /* ── Hero ── */

  .page-hero {
    background: var(--forge-color-surface);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
    padding: var(--forge-space-16) var(--forge-space-6) var(--forge-space-12);
  }

  .hero-inner {
    max-width: var(--forge-layout-max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .hero-eyebrow {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--forge-color-accent);
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-4);
  }

  .hero-headline {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-display);
    font-size: clamp(var(--forge-font-size-3xl), 5vw, var(--forge-font-size-5xl));
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-6);
  }

  .hero-subhead {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-lg);
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    max-width: 58ch;
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-4);
    line-height: var(--forge-line-height-relaxed);
  }

  .hero-meta {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .inline-link {
    color: var(--forge-color-accent);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: var(--forge-color-accent-subtle);
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
    transition: text-decoration-color 0.15s ease;
  }

  .inline-link:hover {
    text-decoration-color: var(--forge-color-accent);
  }

  .inline-link:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid var(--forge-color-accent);
    outline-offset: 2px;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  /* ── ToC ── */

  .toc-nav {
    background: var(--forge-color-surface-raised);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
    padding: var(--forge-space-4) var(--forge-space-6);
  }

  .toc-inner {
    max-width: var(--forge-layout-max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: var(--forge-space-4);
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .toc-label {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xs);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .toc-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--forge-space-1) var(--forge-space-4);
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    counter-reset: toc;
  }

  .toc-link {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.15s ease;
  }

  .toc-link:hover {
    color: var(--forge-color-accent);
  }

  .toc-link:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid var(--forge-color-accent);
    outline-offset: 2px;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  /* ── Content body ── */

  .content-body {
    padding: var(--forge-space-12) var(--forge-space-6);
  }

  .content-inner {
    max-width: var(--forge-layout-max-width);
    margin: 0 auto;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--forge-space-16);
  }

  /* ── Concept sections ── */

  .concept-section {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 48px 1fr;
    gap: var(--forge-space-4) var(--forge-space-8);
    padding-bottom: var(--forge-space-12);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
  }

  .concept-section:last-of-type {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .concept-label {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-mono);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--forge-color-accent-subtle);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    padding-top: 6px;
  }

  .concept-heading {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-display);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-2xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .concept-section p {
    grid-column: 2;
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
  }

  .concept-section code {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-mono);
    font-size: 0.88em;
    background: var(--forge-color-surface-raised);
    border: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
    border-radius: var(--forge-radius-sm);
    padding: 0.1em 0.35em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
  }

  .concept-ref {
    grid-column: 2;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .concept-ref-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--forge-color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
    gap: var(--forge-space-1);
    transition: gap 0.15s ease;
  }

  .concept-ref-link:hover {
    gap: var(--forge-space-2);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }

  .concept-ref-link:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid var(--forge-color-accent);
    outline-offset: 2px;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 540px) {
    .concept-section {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .concept-label {
      display: none;
    }

    .concept-section p,
    .concept-ref {
      grid-column: 1;
    }
  }

  /* ── Diagram section ── */

  .diagram-section {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--forge-space-4);
  }

  .diagram-heading {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-display);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .diagram-lead {
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 68ch;
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    line-height: var(--forge-line-height-relaxed);
  }

  /* ── Flow section ── */

  .flow-section {
    background: var(--forge-color-surface-raised);
    border: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
    border-radius: var(--forge-radius-lg);
    padding: var(--forge-space-10) var(--forge-space-10);
  }

  .flow-heading {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-display);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-2);
  }

  .flow-lead {
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-8);
  }

  .flow-list {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--forge-space-5);
  }

  .flow-item {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--forge-space-4);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .flow-step-badge {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 28px;
    height: 28px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--forge-color-accent);
    color: white;
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-mono);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 1px;
  }

  .flow-step-content {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
    line-height: var(--forge-line-height-relaxed);
  }

  .flow-step-content strong {
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  @media (max-width: 540px) {
    .flow-section {
      padding: var(--forge-space-6);
    }
  }

  /* ── Bottom nav ── */

  .bottom-nav-section {
    padding-top: var(--forge-space-4);
  }

  .bottom-nav-heading {
    font-family: var(--forge-font-family-display);
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
    margin: 0 0 var(--forge-space-6);
  }

  .bottom-nav-links {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
    gap: var(--forge-space-3);
  }

  .bottom-nav-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--forge-space-1);
    padding: var(--forge-space-5);
    background: var(--forge-color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--forge-color-border);
    border-radius: var(--forge-radius-lg);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: border-color 0.15s ease, transform 0.1s ease;
  }

  .bottom-nav-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--forge-color-accent);
    transform: translateY(-1px);
  }

  .bottom-nav-card:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid var(--forge-color-accent);
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }

  .bottom-nav-card-title {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--forge-color-text-strong);
  }

  .bottom-nav-card-desc {
    font-size: var(--forge-font-size-sm);
    color: var(--forge-color-text-muted);
  }
</style>
